  ],
  "footnotes": [
    "Spring and Autumn Period (770–476 BCE): Named after the Spring and Autumn Annals; saw decline of Zhou authority and rise of hegemonic states (齐·晋·楚·吴·越).",
    "Warring States Period (475–221 BCE): Seven major states (战国七雄: 齐·楚·秦·燕·赵·魏·韩) competed until Qin's unification under Qin Shi Huang.",
    "Three Kingdoms (220–280): Division into Wei, Shu, and Wu following Eastern Han collapse; immortalized in the Romance of the Three Kingdoms.",
    "An Lushan Rebellion (755–763): Devastating revolt that killed an estimated 13–36 million and permanently weakened Tang central authority.",
    "Jingkang Incident (1127): Jurchen Jin forces captured Kaifeng and took Emperor Qinzong prisoner, forcing the Song court to flee south.",
    "Taiping Heavenly Kingdom (1851–1864): Pseudo-Christian millenarian revolt led by Hong Xiuquan; one of history's deadliest conflicts with ~20–30 million dead.",
    "Manchukuo (1932–1945): Japanese puppet state in Manchuria with the last Qing emperor Puyi as nominal ruler.",
    "Chinese Civil War (1927–1949): Intermittent conflict between Nationalist KMT and Communist CPC, ending with PRC on the mainland and ROC retreat to Taiwan."
